{"title_page": "Norfolk Island Airport", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name = Norfolk Island Airport\n| image = Norfolk terminal.JPG\n| IATA = NLK\n| ICAO = YSNF\n| type = Public\n| owner = Government of Norfolk Island\n| operator = Administration of Norfolk Island\n| city-served = [[Norfolk Island]]\n| location = <!-- if different than above -->\n| elevation-f = 371\n| website = [http://www.airport.gov.nf/ www.airport.gov.nf]\n| coordinates = {{coord|29|02|33|S|167|56|17|E|region:NF|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map = Oceania\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location of airport on map of [[Oceania]]\n| pushpin_label = '''NLK'''\n| metric-rwy = y\n| r1-number = 11/29\n| r1-length-m = 1,950\n| r1-surface = [[Asphalt]]\n| r2-number = 04/22\n| r2-length-m = 1,435\n| r2-surface = [[Asphalt]]\n| stat-year = 2010/11\n| stat1-header = Passengers\n| stat1-data = 57,758<ref name=\"fiscal\"/>\n| stat2-header = Aircraft movements\n| stat2-data = 872<ref name=\"fiscal\"/>\n| footnotes = Sources: Australian [[Aeronautical Information Publication|AIP]] and aerodrome chart<ref name=\"AIP\">{{AIP AU|YSNF|name=Norfolk Island}}, [http://www.airservicesaustralia.com/aip/current/dap/MYBAD01-130.pdf Aeronautical Chart] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120410115245/http://www.airservicesaustralia.com/aip/current/dap/MYBAD01-130.pdf |date=10 April 2012 }}</ref><br>Passenger and aircraft movements from the [[Department of Infrastructure and Regional Development#Bureau of Infrastructure, Transport and Regional Economics|Bureau of Infrastructure, Transport and Regional Economics (BITRE)]]<ref name=\"BITRE\"/>\n}}\n\n'''Norfolk Island Airport''' {{airport codes|NLK|YSNF}}, also referred to as Norfolk Island International Airport, is the only airport on [[Norfolk Island]], an [[States and territories of Australia|external territory of Australia]]. The island is located in the [[Pacific Ocean]] between [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]], and [[New Caledonia]]. The airport is operated by the Administration of Norfolk Island,<ref name=\"AIP\" /> and is on the west side of the island.\n\n== History ==\nIn August 1942, the [[United States Army Air Forces]] requested that the Australian government construct an aerodrome on Norfolk Island for use by its heavy bombers. It was built by the [[Civil Constructional Corps]], comprising volunteers from New South Wales government departments. The corps was assisted by island residents, with about 300 men employed in total. The first runway was completed in late 1942, with a [[Royal New Zealand Air Force]] (RNZAF) plane landing on Christmas Day. The second runway was opened in February 1943, and the workers left the following month.\n\nThe construction of the runways necessitated the destruction of Pine Avenue, a local landmark consisting of about 500 [[Norfolk Island pine]]s reaching up to {{convert|170|ft|m}} in height.<ref name=clune>{{cite book|title=The Norfolk Island Story|pages=302\u2013303|author=Frank Clune|publisher=Angus & Robertson|year=1967}}</ref> As Norfolk Island did not have enough flat ground, in 1942 several bulldozers were used to knock the tops off several hills, and fill in the valleys between them. Steel mesh was then used to make a solid surface.<ref>[[James A. Michener]]'s short story ''Mutiny'' from the [[Tales of the South Pacific]] collection, roughly and fictionally portrays the decision making process of cutting down obstructing pine trees.</ref>\n\nThe airfield was never used as an operational base, but \"was available to the Allies for use as a staging depot, a refuge for aircraft in distress, and a possible base for anti-submarine patrols\". An RNZAF Radar Unit operated on the island as a navigational aid,<ref name=clune/> and it became a stopover for aircraft travelling between Australia, New Caledonia, New Zealand and the [[Solomon Islands]]. The RNZAF left the airfield in July 1946. At the airfield was an [[air-sea rescue]] unit, a servicing section and a [[radar]] unit installation at [[Mount Bates]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzetc.org/tm/scholarly/tei-WH2Paci-_N89892.html|title=III: Norfolk Island - NZETC|website=www.nzetc.org|accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Light aircraft transit ==\nNorfolk Island is an important transit and refueling point for light aircraft flying between Australia, New Zealand, and the [[Pacific Islands]].\n\nLocated {{Convert|852|km|abbr=on}} southeast of Norfolk is [[Kaitaia Airport]] the most northerly airfield in New Zealand, {{Convert|754|km|abbr=on}} north is [[La Tontouta International Airport|Noum\u00e9a Airport]] in New Caledonia, and {{Convert|900|km|abbr=on}} west is [[Lord Howe Island Airport]] which is {{Convert|600|km|abbr=on}} to the Australian mainland.\n\nThese distances are within the range of many light aircraft when fitted with long range tanks, while the direct distance without using Norfolk Island as a stepping stone, is usually beyond their capabilities.\n\nFrom New Caledonia other Pacific Islands such as [[Vanuatu]] and [[Fiji]] are within range and can be used as further 'stepping stones' to the other South Pacific and North Pacific destinations.\n\n== Facilities ==\nThe airport is at an [[elevation]] of {{convert|371|ft|0|abbr=on}} above [[sea level]]. It has two [[asphalt]] paved [[runway]]s: 11/29 measuring {{convert|1950|x|45|m|0|abbr=on}} and 04/22 measuring {{convert|1435|x|30|m|0|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"AIP\" /> The airport is staffed by a single air traffic controller.\n\nThe airport has a small passenger terminal building which includes waiting areas as well as processing areas for check in (4 counters), security, emigration control, customs control (Norfolk Customs), baggage reclaim and immigration control (Norfolk Immigration Office). A small cafe (Airport Cafe) is open prior to departing flights.\n\nA small cargo terminal building is located next to passenger terminal.\n\nAirport power is provided by the onsite Norfolk Airport Diesel Power Station.\n\nA small carpark is located at the front entrance of the terminal.\n\nThe airport can handle small general aviation aircraft up to a jetliner such as the [[Narrow-body aircraft|narrow-body]] [[Airbus A320]].<ref name=\"norfolkisland.gov.nf\">{{cite web|url=http://www.norfolkisland.gov.nf/niservices/niservices.html#airport|title=Norfolk Island Regional Council|website=www.norfolkisland.gov.nf|accessdate=13 June 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204031012/http://www.norfolkisland.gov.nf/niservices/niservices.html#airport|archivedate=4 February 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Rescue and fire services==\nAviation Rescue and Fire Fighting Service of the Norfolk Island Fire Service provides firefighting service for the airport.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.norfolkisland.gov.nf/niservices/niservices.html#fire|title=Norfolk Island Regional Council|website=www.norfolkisland.gov.nf|accessdate=13 June 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204031012/http://www.norfolkisland.gov.nf/niservices/niservices.html#fire|archivedate=4 February 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe airport fire and rescue has two airport fire tenders. Two new [[Rosenbauer]] Panther ARFF replaced two 1960s era [[Thornycroft]] Nubian Mk 1 6x6 airport tenders in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fire-engine-photos.com/picture/number16333.asp|title=Fire Engines Photos - New Rosenbauer Panthers Norfolk Island|website=www.fire-engine-photos.com|accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref> A new fire station is being built to replace the current building to house the new fire engines.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livinglibrary.edu.nf/_/Fire_Services.html|title=norfolk island emergency services|website=www.livinglibrary.edu.nf|accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Airlines and destinations ==\n\n=== Passenger ===\n{{Airport-dest-list\n|[[Air Chathams]] | [[Auckland Airport|Auckland]]<ref>https://www.airchathams.co.nz/library/files/directflightstonorfolk.pdf</ref>\n| [[Air New Zealand]] | [[Brisbane Airport|Brisbane]], [[Sydney Airport|Sydney]]\n}}\n\n=== Notes ===\nAir New Zealand's services to Norfolk Island consists of two flight per week from Brisbane and three flights per week from Sydney. On 16 December 2016, Air New Zealand announced it was ceasing its flight services between Norfolk Island and Auckland citing low passenger numbers. The last flight was on 21 May 2017. Air New Zealand continues to operate flights between the airport and Brisbane and Sydney with [[Airbus A320]] aircraft.<ref>https://www.airnewzealand.com</ref>\n\nNorfolk Island Airlines services were operated with Nauru Airlines [[Boeing 737-300]]s.<ref>http://www.nauruairlines.com.au</ref>\n\n[[Norfolk Jet Express]] operated from the airport from 1997 to 2005 and [[Norfolk Air]] from 2006 to 2012.  In 1996, [[Ansett Australia]] was operating nonstop [[Boeing 737-300]] jet service between the airport and Sydney four days a week.<ref>http://www.departedflights.com, Oct. 1, 1996 Official Airline Guide (OAG), Sydney-Norfolk Island flight schedules</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\n\nThe airport is connected to the rest of the island by Douglas Drive.\n\nTransportation to and from the airport can be made by taxi, private car hires or local hotel shuttles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.norfolkonlinenews.com/transport.html|title=Getting around on Norfolk Island|website=www.norfolkonlinenews.com|accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\nNorfolk Island Airport was [[List of the busiest airports in Australia|ranked 56th in Australia]] for the number of [[revenue passenger]]s served in [[financial year]] 2010-2011.<ref name=\"fiscal\">[[Fiscal year]] 1 July - 30 June</ref><ref name=\"BITRE\">{{cite web | url = http://www.bitre.gov.au/publications/ongoing/files/WebAirport_FY_1986-2011.xls | title = Airport Traffic Data 1985-86 to 2010-11 | publisher = [[Department of Infrastructure and Regional Development#Bureau of Infrastructure, Transport and Regional Economics|Bureau of Infrastructure, Transport and Regional Economics (BITRE)]] | date = May 2012 | accessdate = 27 June 2012 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120324180211/https://www.bitre.gov.au/publications/ongoing/files/WebAirport_FY_1986-2011.xls | archivedate = 24 March 2012 | df = dmy-all }} Refers to \"Regular Public Transport (RPT) operations only\"</ref>\n{{Bar graph\n| title = Annual passenger and aircraft statistics for Norfolk Island<ref name=\"BITRE\" />\n| bar_width = 18\n| width_units = em\n| label_type = Year<ref name=\"fiscal\"/>\n| label1 = 2001-02\n| label2 = 2002-03\n| label3 = 2003-04\n| label4 = 2004-05\n| label5 = 2005-06\n| label6 = 2006-07\n| label7 = 2007-08\n| label8 = 2008-09\n| label9 = 2009-10\n| label10 = 2010-11\n| data_type = Revenue passengers\n| data_max = 83,000\n| data1 = 59,562\n| data2 = 72,781\n| data3 = 81,470\n| data4 = 72,801\n| data5 = 62,483\n| data6 = 73,163\n| data7 = 75,925\n| data8 = 64,782\n| data9 = 61,594\n| data10 = 57,758\n| col2_data_type = Aircraft movements\n| col2_data_max = 1,250\n| col2_data1 = 744\n| col2_data2 = 1,091\n| col2_data3 = 1,199\n| col2_data4 = 939\n| col2_data5 = 691\n| col2_data6 = 913\n| col2_data7 = 1,027\n| col2_data8 = 951\n| col2_data9 = 863\n| col2_data10 = 872\n}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of airports in territories of Australia]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.airport.gov.nf/|Norfolk Island Airport official website}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{Oceania in topic|List of airports in}}\n\n[[Category:Airports in territories of Australia]]\n[[Category:Aviation in Norfolk Island]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Norfolk Island]]\n[[Category:1942 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Airports established in 1942]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name = Norfolk Island Airport\n| image = Norfolk terminal.JPG\n| IATA = NLK\n| ICAO = YSNF\n| type = Public\n| owner = Government of Norfolk Island\n| operator = Administration of Norfolk Island\n| city-served = [[Norfolk Island]]\n| location = <!-- if different than above -->\n| elevation-f = 371\n| website = [http://www.airport.gov.nf/ www.airport.gov.nf]\n| coordinates = {{coord|29|02|33|S|167|56|17|E|region:NF|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map = Oceania\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location of airport on map of [[Oceania]]\n| pushpin_label = '''NLK'''\n| metric-rwy = y\n| r1-number = 11/29\n| r1-length-m = 1,950\n| r1-surface = [[Asphalt]]\n| r2-number = 04/22\n| r2-length-m = 1,435\n| r2-surface = [[Asphalt]]\n| stat-year = 2010/11\n| stat1-header = Passengers\n| stat1-data = 57,758<ref name=\"fiscal\"/>\n| stat2-header = Aircraft movements\n| stat2-data = 872<ref name=\"fiscal\"/>\n| footnotes = Sources: Australian [[Aeronautical Information Publication|AIP]] and aerodrome chart<ref name=\"AIP\">{{AIP AU|YSNF|name=Norfolk Island}}, [http://www.airservicesaustralia.com/aip/current/dap/MYBAD01-130.pdf Aeronautical Chart] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120410115245/http://www.airservicesaustralia.com/aip/current/dap/MYBAD01-130.pdf |date=10 April 2012 }}</ref><br>Passenger and aircraft movements from the [[Department of Infrastructure and Regional Development#Bureau of Infrastructure, Transport and Regional Economics|Bureau of Infrastructure, Transport and Regional Economics (BITRE)]]<ref name=\"BITRE\"/>\n}}\n\n'''Norfolk Island Airport''' {{airport codes|NLK|YSNF}}, also referred to as Norfolk Island International Airport, is the only airport on [[Norfolk Island]], an [[States and territories of Australia|external territory of Australia]]. The island is located in the [[Pacific Ocean]] between [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]], and [[New Caledonia]]. The airport is operated by the Administration of Norfolk Island,<ref name=\"AIP\" /> and is on the west side of the island.\n\n== History ==\nIn August 1942, the [[United States Army Air Forces]] requested that the Australian government construct an aerodrome on Norfolk Island for use by its heavy bombers. It was built by the [[Civil Constructional Corps]], comprising volunteers from New South Wales government departments. The corps was assisted by island residents, with about 300 men employed in total. The first runway was completed in late 1942, with a [[Royal New Zealand Air Force]] (RNZAF) plane landing on Christmas Day. The second runway was opened in February 1943, and the workers left the following month.\n\nThe construction of the runways necessitated the destruction of Pine Avenue, a local landmark consisting of about 500 [[Norfolk Island pine]]s reaching up to {{convert|170|ft|m}} in height.<ref name=clune>{{cite book|title=The Norfolk Island Story|pages=302\u2013303|author=Frank Clune|publisher=Angus & Robertson|year=1967}}</ref> As Norfolk Island did not have enough flat ground, in 1942 several bulldozers were used to knock the tops off several hills, and fill in the valleys between them. Steel mesh was then used to make a solid surface.<ref>[[James A. Michener]]'s short story ''Mutiny'' from the [[Tales of the South Pacific]] collection, roughly and fictionally portrays the decision making process of cutting down obstructing pine trees.</ref>\n\nThe airfield was never used as an operational base, but \"was available to the Allies for use as a staging depot, a refuge for aircraft in distress, and a possible base for anti-submarine patrols\". An RNZAF Radar Unit operated on the island as a navigational aid,<ref name=clune/> and it became a stopover for aircraft travelling between Australia, New Caledonia, New Zealand and the [[Solomon Islands]]. The RNZAF left the airfield in July 1946. At the airfield was an [[air-sea rescue]] unit, a servicing section and a [[radar]] unit installation at [[Mount Bates]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzetc.org/tm/scholarly/tei-WH2Paci-_N89892.html|title=III: Norfolk Island - NZETC|website=www.nzetc.org|accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Light aircraft transit ==\nNorfolk Island is an important transit and refueling point for light aircraft flying between Australia, New Zealand, and the [[Pacific Islands]].\n\nLocated {{Convert|852|km|abbr=on}} southeast of Norfolk is [[Kaitaia Airport]] the most northerly airfield in New Zealand, {{Convert|754|km|abbr=on}} north is [[La Tontouta International Airport|Noum\u00e9a Airport]] in New Caledonia, and {{Convert|900|km|abbr=on}} west is [[Lord Howe Island Airport]] which is {{Convert|600|km|abbr=on}} to the Australian mainland.\n\nThese distances are within the range of many light aircraft when fitted with long range tanks, while the direct distance without using Norfolk Island as a stepping stone, is usually beyond their capabilities.\n\nFrom New Caledonia other Pacific Islands such as [[Vanuatu]] and [[Fiji]] are within range and can be used as further 'stepping stones' to the other South Pacific and North Pacific destinations.\n\n== Facilities ==\nThe airport is at an [[elevation]] of {{convert|371|ft|0|abbr=on}} above [[sea level]]. It has two [[asphalt]] paved [[runway]]s: 11/29 measuring {{convert|1950|x|45|m|0|abbr=on}} and 04/22 measuring {{convert|1435|x|30|m|0|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"AIP\" /> The airport is staffed by a single air traffic controller.\n\nThe airport has a small passenger terminal building which includes waiting areas as well as processing areas for check in (4 counters), security, emigration control, customs control (Norfolk Customs), baggage reclaim and immigration control (Norfolk Immigration Office). A small cafe (Airport Cafe) is open prior to departing flights.\n\nA small cargo terminal building is located next to passenger terminal.\n\nAirport power is provided by the onsite Norfolk Airport Diesel Power Station.\n\nA small carpark is located at the front entrance of the terminal.\n\nThe airport can handle small general aviation aircraft up to a jetliner such as the [[Narrow-body aircraft|narrow-body]] [[Airbus A320]].<ref name=\"norfolkisland.gov.nf\">{{cite web|url=http://www.norfolkisland.gov.nf/niservices/niservices.html#airport|title=Norfolk Island Regional Council|website=www.norfolkisland.gov.nf|accessdate=13 June 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204031012/http://www.norfolkisland.gov.nf/niservices/niservices.html#airport|archivedate=4 February 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Rescue and fire services==\nAviation Rescue and Fire Fighting Service of the Norfolk Island Fire Service provides firefighting service for the airport.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.norfolkisland.gov.nf/niservices/niservices.html#fire|title=Norfolk Island Regional Council|website=www.norfolkisland.gov.nf|accessdate=13 June 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204031012/http://www.norfolkisland.gov.nf/niservices/niservices.html#fire|archivedate=4 February 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe airport fire and rescue has two airport fire tenders. Two new [[Rosenbauer]] Panther ARFF replaced two 1960s era [[Thornycroft]] Nubian Mk 1 6x6 airport tenders in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fire-engine-photos.com/picture/number16333.asp|title=Fire Engines Photos - New Rosenbauer Panthers Norfolk Island|website=www.fire-engine-photos.com|accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref> A new fire station is being built to replace the current building to house the new fire engines.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livinglibrary.edu.nf/_/Fire_Services.html|title=norfolk island emergency services|website=www.livinglibrary.edu.nf|accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Airlines and destinations ==\n\n=== Passenger ===\n{{Airport-dest-list\n|[[Air Chathams]] | [[Auckland Airport|Auckland]]<ref>https://www.airchathams.co.nz/library/files/directflightstonorfolk.pdf</ref>\n| [[Air New Zealand]] | [[Brisbane Airport|Brisbane]], [[Sydney Airport|Sydney]]\n}}\n\n=== Notes ===\nAir New Zealand's services to Norfolk Island consists of two flight per week from Brisbane and three flights per week from Sydney. On 16 December 2016, Air New Zealand announced it was ceasing its flight services between Norfolk Island and Auckland citing low passenger numbers. The last flight was on 21 May 2017. Air New Zealand continues to operate flights between the airport and Brisbane and Sydney with [[Airbus A320]] aircraft.<ref>https://www.airnewzealand.com</ref>\n\nNorfolk Island Airlines services were operated with Nauru Airlines [[Boeing 737-300]]s.<ref>http://www.nauruairlines.com.au</ref>\n\n[[Norfolk Jet Express]] operated from the airport from 1997 to 2005 and [[Norfolk Air]] from 2006 to 2012.  In 1996, [[Ansett Australia]] was operating nonstop [[Boeing 737-300]] jet service between the airport and Sydney four days a week.<ref>http://www.departedflights.com, Oct. 1, 1996 Official Airline Guide (OAG), Sydney-Norfolk Island flight schedules</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\n\nThe airport is connected to the rest of the island by Douglas Drive.\n\nTransportation to and from the airport can be made by taxi, private car hires or local hotel shuttles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.norfolkonlinenews.com/transport.html|title=Getting around on Norfolk Island|website=www.norfolkonlinenews.com|accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\nNorfolk Island Airport was [[List of the busiest airports in Australia|ranked 56th in Australia]] for the number of [[revenue passenger]]s served in [[financial year]] 2010-2011.<ref name=\"fiscal\">[[Fiscal year]] 1 July - 30 June</ref><ref name=\"BITRE\">{{cite web | url = http://www.bitre.gov.au/publications/ongoing/files/WebAirport_FY_1986-2011.xls | title = Airport Traffic Data 1985-86 to 2010-11 | publisher = [[Department of Infrastructure and Regional Development#Bureau of Infrastructure, Transport and Regional Economics|Bureau of Infrastructure, Transport and Regional Economics (BITRE)]] | date = May 2012 | accessdate = 27 June 2